  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>Bear Notes App Review</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · 11 min read</div>
      <div class="author">By <a href={`/authors/${authorSlug}`}>{author}</a></div>

      <Image src={heroImg} alt="Bear notes app on a Mac showing a Markdown note with nested tags" width={1200} height={600} loading="eager" fetchpriority="high" class="hero-img" />

      <ProductCTACard
        productName={productName}
        brand={brand}
        rating={ratingValue}
        price={bestPrice}
        slug={productSlug}
        editorChoice={false}
      />

      <ReviewMeta
        authorSlug={authorSlug}
        lastUpdated={lastUpdated}
        testingDuration={testingDuration}
        productsTested={productsTested}
      />

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily notes, drafts, and research</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> <strong>Bear</strong> is the best Apple-only Markdown notes app for writers and personal knowledge workers. The editor is beautiful and fast, nested tags replace folders elegantly, and iCloud sync is reliable across iPhone, iPad, and Mac. The Apple-only limit and lack of collaboration are real constraints, but if you live in the Apple ecosystem and want a focused writing app, Bear is hard to beat at $2.99/month.
      </div>

      <p>Bear launched in 2016 as a cleaner alternative to Apple Notes and Evernote, and it has built a loyal following among Apple-only users who want a fast, beautiful Markdown editor. The app is free to use on a single device, with a Bear Pro subscription ($2.99/month or $28/year) unlocking iCloud sync, extra themes, and export to PDF, Word, and HTML. We subscribed to Pro and spent 60 days using Bear as our primary notes app across a Mac, an iPad, and an iPhone to see whether it holds up against Obsidian and Notion.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against the two biggest alternatives, see our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> breakdown, and for a deeper look at a free cross-platform option, see our <a href="/reviews/obsidian-review/">Obsidian review</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>The Editor: Beautiful Markdown With Live Preview</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of Bear is its editor, which renders Markdown inline rather than showing a split-pane preview. Type **bold** and the text immediately renders as bold; type # Heading and the line becomes a styled heading. This live-preview approach is faster than the split-pane editors in Obsidian and Typora, and it makes Bear feel like a native Apple app rather than a developer tool. The typography is excellent, with adjustable font sizes, line heights, and seven built-in themes (four light, three dark).</p>

      <p>In our 60-day test, we drafted blog posts, meeting notes, research outlines, and a short story in Bear, and the editor held up well across all formats. Code blocks render with syntax highlighting for over 150 languages, and markdown tables display inline. The one editor limitation is no rich-content embedding — you cannot drop in a database, kanban board, or embedded spreadsheet. Bear is a text-first app, and if you need structured content, Notion is the better fit.</p>

      <p>The distraction-free writing mode hides the sidebar, toolbar, and tag pane, leaving only the text and a minimal status bar. We used this mode for long-form drafting and found it genuinely helpful — the app fades into the background, and the typography carries the experience. The mode is one keystroke (Cmd-Option-D) and restores instantly when you need the chrome back.</p>

      <h3>Organization: Nested Tags Instead of Folders</h3>
      <p>Bear replaces folders with nested tags, and the system works better than it sounds. A note tagged #work/projects/toolstep/bear-review appears in the sidebar under Work, then Projects, then Toolstep, then Bear Review — a four-level hierarchy built from a single tag. You can assign multiple tags to a note, so the same note can live under #work and #research without duplication. The tag pane collapses and expands like a folder tree, so navigation feels familiar.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is discipline. Without an enforced folder hierarchy, tags can multiply unchecked — we ended up with 47 tags after 60 days, several of which were near-duplicates (#ideas and #idea, #work and #projects/work). Bear has no tag-merging tool, so cleanup is manual. For users who treat tags as ad-hoc labels, this is fine; for users who want a strict taxonomy, folders (as in Obsidian) may be more predictable.</p>

      <p>Search is fast and supports tag filters, full-text queries, and date ranges. We searched across 312 notes in our test library and results appeared instantly as we typed. Bear uses Apple's Core Data and Spotlight indexing, so search is faster than the third-party search in Obsidian and matches Apple Notes in speed. The search bar supports Markdown operators (tag:work -tag:draft) for power queries, which is a nice touch.</p>

      <h3>Cross-Note Linking and the Knowledge Graph</h3>
      <p>Bear supports wiki-style cross-note linking with [[double brackets]]. Type [[bear-review]] and Bear creates a link to the note titled "Bear Review," and the linked note gains a backlink to the source. The backlinks panel (in the right sidebar) shows every note that links to the current note, which is the foundation of a personal knowledge graph or second brain.</p>

      <p>In our testing, we used cross-note linking to connect research notes to draft outlines, and the backlinks panel made it easy to trace connections. The system works reliably, but Bear lacks graph visualization — there is no way to see your knowledge graph as a visual map, as Obsidian offers. For users who think visually, this is a real limitation. For users who navigate by search and backlinks, Bear's system is sufficient.</p>

      <p>Bear does not support block references (linking to a specific paragraph rather than a whole note), which is a power feature in Obsidian and Roam Research. Most users will not miss this, but researchers building dense interlinked notes may find the limitation frustrating. Bear is a notes app first and a knowledge graph second — the linking is there, but it is not the central feature.</p>

      <h3>Sync and Platforms: iCloud and Apple-Only</h3>
      <p>Bear Pro syncs across iPhone, iPad, and Mac via iCloud, and the sync is fast and reliable. In our 60-day test, edits on one device appeared on the others within 5 to 10 seconds, and we experienced no merge conflicts or data loss. The sync runs on Apple's CloudKit infrastructure, which means your notes are encrypted in transit and at rest on Apple's servers, and Bear does not have access to your content — a privacy advantage over Notion and Evernote, which store data on their own servers.</p>

      <p>The hard limitation is platforms. Bear is Apple-only — there is no Windows app, no Android app, and no web version. If you use a Windows PC at work or an Android phone, you cannot access your Bear notes on those devices. The developer, Shiny Frog, has stated that Bear is built on Apple-native frameworks (Swift, Core Data, TextKit) and a port would require a full rewrite. For Apple-only users, this is a non-issue; for cross-platform users, it is a dealbreaker.</p>

      <p>The free tier of Bear stores notes locally on a single device with no sync. This is genuinely useful — you can use Bear free forever on a single Mac or iPhone, and only pay for Pro if you add a second device. The free tier includes all editing, tagging, and linking features; Pro only unlocks sync, the extra themes, and export to PDF, Word, HTML, and JPEG. This is one of the most generous free tiers in the notes-app category.</p>

      <h3>Export and Interoperability</h3>
      <p>Bear Pro exports notes to Markdown, PDF, HTML, Word, and JPEG. The Markdown export is the most useful for interoperability — it produces clean .md files that open in Obsidian, Typora, VS Code, or any text editor. The PDF export preserves themes and typography, producing attractive documents for sharing. The Word export is decent but strips some Bear-specific syntax (like the tag-line at the top of a note), requiring manual cleanup.</p>

      <p>The limitation is that Bear stores notes in a proprietary Core Data database, not as individual Markdown files on disk. This is different from Obsidian, which stores notes as plain .md files in a folder you control. Bear's approach is faster for search and sync, but it means you cannot point another app at your Bear library, and if Bear ever shuts down, exporting all your notes is a multi-step batch process rather than a simple folder copy.</p>

      <p>For most users, the export options are sufficient. If you want file-system-level control over your notes, Obsidian is the better choice. If you want a polished app that handles storage and sync for you, Bear's trade-off is reasonable. We exported our 312-note library to Markdown at the end of the test, and the process took about 5 minutes via the batch export feature.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>Bear competes against Obsidian, Notion, and Apple Notes. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>App</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Platforms</th>
            <th>Markdown</th>
            <th>Sync</th>
            <th>Plugins</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Bear (Pro)</strong></td>
            <td>$2.99/mo</td>
            <td>Apple only</td>
            <td>Live preview</td>
            <td>iCloud</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Obsidian</td>
            <td>$8/mo (Sync)</td>
            <td>Win/Mac/Linux/iOS/Android</td>
            <td>Split-pane</td>
            <td>Paid add-on</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Notion</td>
            <td>$10/mo (Plus)</td>
            <td>All platforms + web</td>
            <td>Block-based</td>
            <td>Built-in</td>
            <td>API only</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Apple Notes</td>
            <td>Free</td>
            <td>Apple only</td>
            <td>Rich text</td>
            <td>iCloud</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Obsidian</strong> is the closest alternative for Markdown purists. It is free, cross-platform, stores notes as plain .md files, and has a deep plugin ecosystem. The trade-off is a steeper learning curve, a less polished editor, and paid add-ons for sync ($8/month) and publish ($10/month). Choose Obsidian if you want cross-platform access, plugins, or file-system control; choose Bear if you want a cleaner, Apple-native experience. See our <a href="/reviews/obsidian-review/">Obsidian review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p><strong>Notion</strong> is the team-friendly alternative. It supports databases, kanban boards, real-time collaboration, and works on every platform including web. The trade-off is a heavier, block-based editor that is slower for pure writing, and a $10/month Plus plan for teams. Choose Notion if you need collaboration or structured content; choose Bear if you want focused writing. See our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> comparison for the deeper analysis.</p>

      <p><strong>Apple Notes</strong> is the free Apple-only alternative. It is pre-installed on every iPhone, iPad, and Mac, supports iCloud sync, and has added Markdown-style formatting and inline scanning. The trade-off is no native Markdown export, no cross-note linking, and a less powerful editor. For casual note-takers, Apple Notes is enough; for writers and knowledge workers, Bear is a meaningful upgrade.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Subscribe to Bear Pro if you use more than one Apple device and want a fast, beautiful Markdown notes app. The iCloud sync alone justifies the $2.99/month, and the extra themes and export formats are a bonus. Choose the annual plan ($28/year) to save about $8 compared to monthly billing.</p>

      <p>Use Bear free if you only have one Apple device. The free tier includes all editing, tagging, and linking features — you only need Pro for sync, extra themes, and export. Many users can use Bear free indefinitely without missing the paid features.</p>

      <p>Skip Bear and use Obsidian if you need Windows, Android, or Linux access, or if you want plugins and file-system control over your notes. Obsidian is free and cross-platform, with paid add-ons only for sync and publish. See our <a href="/reviews/obsidian-review/">Obsidian review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>Use Notion instead if you need team collaboration, databases, or a web app. Notion costs more ($10/month for Plus), but it is the better tool for structured content and shared workspaces. Bear is a single-user writing app, not a team tool.</p>

      <p>Pair Bear with a <a href="/reviews/best-cloud-storage-2026/">cloud storage service</a> for attachments and backups, and a <a href="/reviews/best-password-managers-2026/">password manager</a> to secure your accounts. If you draft tutorials or research notes, a <a href="/reviews/best-screen-recorders-mac/">screen recorder for Mac</a> rounds out a notes-and-capture workflow.</p>

